theorem Topology.P1_iff_P3_compl_of_isOpen
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} (hA_open : IsOpen A) :
    Topology.P1 (Aᶜ) ↔ Topology.P3 (Aᶜ) := by
  have h_closed : IsClosed (Aᶜ) := hA_open.isClosed_compl
  have h₁ := Topology.P1_iff_P2_compl_of_isClosed (X := X) (A := A) h_closed
  have h₂ := Topology.P2_iff_P3_compl_of_isOpen (X := X) (A := A) hA_open
  simpa using h₁.trans h₂

theorem Topology.closure_eq_interior_union_frontier
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] (A : Set X) :
    closure (A : Set X) = interior A ∪ frontier A := by
  ext x
  constructor
  · intro hx
    by_cases hInt : x ∈ interior A
    · exact Or.inl hInt
    · -- `x` is in the closure of `A` but not in its interior,
      -- hence it belongs to the frontier.
      have hFront : x ∈ frontier (A : Set X) := by
        dsimp [frontier] at *
        exact And.intro hx hInt
      exact Or.inr hFront
  · intro h
    cases h with
    | inl hInt =>
        -- A point of the interior is certainly in the closure.
        have hxA : (x : X) ∈ A := interior_subset hInt
        exact subset_closure hxA
    | inr hFront =>
        -- By definition, a point of the frontier lies in the closure.
        dsimp [frontier] at hFront
        exact hFront.1

theorem Topology.P2_iff_P3_compl_of_isOpen
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} (hA_open : IsOpen A) :
    Topology.P2 (Aᶜ) ↔ Topology.P3 (Aᶜ) := by
  -- The complement of an open set is closed.
  have hA_closed : IsClosed (Aᶜ) := hA_open.isClosed_compl
  -- For a closed set, `P2` and `P3` are equivalent to openness; apply the existing lemma.
  simpa using
    (Topology.P2_iff_P3_of_isClosed (X := X) (A := Aᶜ) hA_closed)

theorem Topology.dense_iff_interior_compl_eq_empty
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    Dense (A : Set X) ↔ interior (Aᶜ : Set X) = (∅ : Set X) := by
  classical
  -- Step 1: `Dense A` is equivalent to `closure A = univ`.
  have h_dense :
      Dense (A : Set X) ↔ closure (A : Set X) = (Set.univ : Set X) :=
    dense_iff_closure_eq (s := (A : Set X))
  -- Step 2: `interior (Aᶜ)` is the complement of `closure A`.
  have h_int_compl :
      interior (Aᶜ : Set X) = (closure (A : Set X))ᶜ := by
    exact interior_compl
  -- Step 3: Rewrite the right–hand side in terms of `closure A = univ`.
  have h_aux :
      closure (A : Set X) = (Set.univ : Set X) ↔
        interior (Aᶜ : Set X) = (∅ : Set X) := by
    constructor
    · intro h_cl
      -- If `closure A = univ`, then `interior (Aᶜ)` is the empty set.
      simpa [h_cl, Set.compl_univ] using h_int_compl
    · intro h_int_empty
      -- From `h_int_compl` and `h_int_empty` we get `(closure A)ᶜ = ∅`.
      have h_compl : (closure (A : Set X))ᶜ = (∅ : Set X) := by
        have : (closure (A : Set X))ᶜ = interior (Aᶜ : Set X) := by
          simpa using h_int_compl.symm
        simpa [h_int_empty] using this
      -- Taking complements gives `closure A = univ`.
      have : closure (A : Set X) = (Set.univ : Set X) := by
        have h1 : closure (A : Set X) = ((closure (A : Set X))ᶜ)ᶜ := by
          ext x
          by_cases hx : (x : X) ∈ closure (A : Set X) <;> simp [hx]
        simpa [h_compl] using h1
      exact this
  -- Combine the two equivalences.
  simpa using h_dense.trans h_aux

theorem Topology.closure_has_P2_of_denseInterior
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    Dense (interior A) → Topology.P2 (closure A) := by
  intro hDense
  -- From the density of `interior A`, we know `closure A` satisfies `P3`.
  have hP3 : Topology.P3 (closure A) :=
    Topology.closure_has_P3_of_denseInterior (X := X) (A := A) hDense
  -- A `P3` closure yields `P2` for the same closure.
  exact Topology.P2_of_P3_closure (X := X) (A := A) hP3
